<subSubSection pageId="41" pageNumber="42" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="41" pageNumber="42">
Commonly collected. Reviewed for Africa by 
<bibRefCitation author="Ferrer-Suay, M" journalOrPublisher="African Entomology" pageId="151" pageNumber="152" pagination="255 - 266" title="A review of Alloxysta species (Hymenoptera: Cynipoidea: Figitidae: Charipinae) from Africa." url="10.4001/003.021.0222" volume="21" year="2013">Ferrer-Suay et al. (2013)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="41" pageNumber="42" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="41" pageNumber="42">
These are the characteristic tiny pale charipines, but in fact they vary a lot in size and colour (also within species!). Colours vary from very dark brown through middle browns and reds to pale yellow, frequently with the head in a paler hue than the rest of the body. The absence of a mesopleural line is the best way to separate them from the otherwise often similar 
<taxonomicName authority="Förster, 1869" authorityName="Förster" authorityYear="1869" class="Insecta" family="Figitidae" genus="Phaenoglyphis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Phaenoglyphis" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Phaenoglyphis</taxonomicName>
. 
<taxonomicName authority="Foerster, 1869" authorityName="Foerster" authorityYear="1869" class="Insecta" family="Figitidae" genus="Dilyta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Dilyta" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Dilyta</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Fergusson, 1986" authorityName="Fergusson" authorityYear="1986" class="Insecta" family="Figitidae" genus="Apocharips" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Apocharips" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Apocharips</taxonomicName>
also lack the mesopleural line, but can be separated by their conjoined two apical antennal articles, or by their characteristic metasoma, which is mostly covered by a syntergite and is oval in shape. The metasoma of a representative of 
<taxonomicName authority="Foerster, 1869" authorityName="Foerster" authorityYear="1869" class="Insecta" family="Figitidae" genus="Alloxysta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Alloxysta" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Alloxysta</taxonomicName>
typically shows the posterior tergites separate, and is truncated at the end, often with a (cynipid-like) oblique slash. Furthermore, most 
<taxonomicName authority="Foerster, 1869" authorityName="Foerster" authorityYear="1869" class="Insecta" family="Figitidae" genus="Alloxysta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Alloxysta" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Alloxysta</taxonomicName>
are larger, paler and more pubescent (on the pronotum, metapleura and coxae) than most 
<taxonomicName authority="Foerster, 1869" authorityName="Foerster" authorityYear="1869" class="Insecta" family="Figitidae" genus="Dilyta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Dilyta" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Dilyta</taxonomicName>
, and the mesoscutum is smoothly convex (rather than the hump of 
<taxonomicName authority="Foerster, 1869" authorityName="Foerster" authorityYear="1869" class="Insecta" family="Figitidae" genus="Dilyta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Dilyta" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Dilyta</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
