</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="41" pageNumber="42" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="41" pageNumber="42">
Worldwide, but most abundant in the Holarctic region. Afrotropical records: Democratic Republic of Congo (
<bibRefCitation author="Benoit, PLG" journalOrPublisher="Revue de Zoologie et de Botanique Africaines" pageId="149" pageNumber="150" pagination="437 - 440" title="Deux Cynipidae-Charipinae inédits du Congo Belge." volume="53" year="1956 e">Benoit 1956e</bibRefCitation>
), Kenya (
<bibRefCitation author="Evenhuis, H" journalOrPublisher="Entomologische Berichten" pageId="151" pageNumber="152" pagination="165 - 168" title="Studies on CynipidaeAlloxystinae 4. Alloxystamacrophadna (Hartig, 1841) and Alloxystabrassicae (Ashmead, 1887)." volume="34" year="1974">Evenhuis 1974</bibRefCitation>
), Madagascar (
<bibRefCitation author="Ferrer-Suay, M" journalOrPublisher="African Entomology" pageId="151" pageNumber="152" pagination="222 - 228" title="First record of Alloxysta Foerster from Madagascar, with descriptions of two new species (Hymenoptera: Cynipoidea: Figitidae: Charipinae)." url="10.4001/003.020.0208" volume="20" year="2012">Ferrer-Suay et al. 2012</bibRefCitation>
), Burundi, Rwanda, South Africa, Uganda, Zimbabwe (
<bibRefCitation author="Ferrer-Suay, M" journalOrPublisher="African Entomology" pageId="151" pageNumber="152" pagination="255 - 266" title="A review of Alloxysta species (Hymenoptera: Cynipoidea: Figitidae: Charipinae) from Africa." url="10.4001/003.021.0222" volume="21" year="2013">Ferrer-Suay and Pujade-Villar 2013</bibRefCitation>
) Ethiopia, Ghana, Namibia, Yemen, Zambia (here). Apparently some species are synanthropically widespread, but there is no reason to assume that none of the forms present in Africa are native.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="41" pageNumber="42" type="biology">
<paragraph pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Biology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="41" pageNumber="42">
Hyperparasitoids attacking aphelinid and aphidiine wasps on aphids. (
<bibRefCitation author="Gutierrez, AP" journalOrPublisher="Annals of the Entomological Society of America" pageId="151" pageNumber="152" pagination="1345 - 1354" title="Studies on host selection and host specificity of the aphid hyperparasite Charipsvictrix (Hymenoptera: Cynipidae). 1. Review of hyperparasitism and the field ecology of Charips victrix." volume="63" year="1970">Gutierrez and van den Bosch 1970</bibRefCitation>
, Evenhuis passim, 
<bibRefCitation author="Andrews, FG" journalOrPublisher="Occasional Papers in Entomology, Calif. Dept. Food Agric." pageId="148" pageNumber="149" pagination="11 - 28" title="Taxonomy and host specificity of Nearctic Alloxystinae with a catalog of the world species (Hymenoptera, Cynipidae)." volume="25" year="1978">Andrews 1978</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Fergusson, NDM" journalOrPublisher="London" pageId="151" pageNumber="152" pagination="1 - 55" title="Handbooks for the Identification of British Insects" year="1986">Fergusson 1986</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
